    public interface Named
    A Named object has an absolute, unique, uniform name in the ans:// naming scheme. ans:// is a (currently unregistered) URI scheme that conforms to a subset of http:// syntax.

    The purpose of ans is to provide a URI naming system that defines a relatively simple, flexible, canonical, and federated identification scheme. Unlike http:// that specifies a name or location on a network, ans specifies a location-independent name. However, using this name, you can obtain objects within a given dominion of objectof.

    The following is the ABNF (rfc5234) syntax: 

     ansName      = "ans://" absoluteName
 absoluteName = authority [pathName ["-" label]]
 authority    = domain ":" release
 pathName     = 1*("/" componentName)
 label        = 1*(ALPHA / esc / DIGIT)
 componentName= *(name ".") name
 name         = (ALPHA / esc) *(ALPHA / esc / DIGIT)
 domain       = 1*(name ".") name
 release      = 5DIGIT / 4DIGIT
 esc          = "__" / "_" 2HEX
 HEX          = DIGIT / %x41-46; uppercase A-F only

    The authority specifies a unique initial context over time. The domain identifies a registered Internet domain or sub-domain thereof. The release value (the "URL port") defines the week in which the authority is defined. The four-digit form is interpreted as YYWW where YY is the year within the 21st century and WW is the week number within the year. The five-digit form is interpreted as YYYWW for releases beyond the 21st century. A dominion is a physical union of multiple authorities and can be considered a view of the objectof web.

    • Domains must be defined by the registered owner of the domain, or a proxy thereof.
    • The release value must lie within a week in which the domain holder is the registered owner of the domain. Note that "WW", although specifying a week, can be any value between 00 and 99 provided it follows the domain ownership restriction. Each release within a domain may be totally independent from other releases within the same domain. A release can be considered a major version change with no assurance of compatibility from other releases: A release shouldn't equate to a version hence a week-by-week identifier should provide an adequate time division.

    The pathName specifies a named path to an object. pathName components may be a compound componentName or a simple name. The hierarchy within a component name, if any, is opaque for the purposes of this scheme and should be "little-endian".

    Names are restricted to a small set of characters consisting of standard Latin letters, digits, and the underscore. However, the underscore begins an esc sequence enabling encoding of any other UTF code point by specifying one or more byte values in sequence exactly representing a UTF-8 encoding of the code point. It is invalid to escape a character not requiring escape, i.e. Latin letters and digits . To escape the "_" itself, use "_5F". The intent is to have names be:

    • inherently canonical enabling simple string comparison for equality.
    • directly represented in code since a name is a valid identifier in many modern computer languages.
    • essentially unambiguous from a human visual perspective. The small set of code points promotes this.
